Mac OS X El Capitan, 10.11.1, 
VSCode 0.10.1
css file size: 116,198 bytes (119 KB on disk)

The attached file was built with a minifier as part of a grunt task to build the distributable files of a website. Tried to open the file several times to make sure that file is the issue. The app eventually shows a dialog that says "Visual Studio is no longer responding" 

When I reopen VSCode after the crash, the folder has been forgotten, it opens to a different folder. When is the "current" folder updated to the existing folder?

I added the .txt extension in order to add it here. The file extension was originally just .css

[main.08642f99.css.txt](https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/files/38262/main.08642f99.css.txt)

1. Go full screen
2. Split it with another app (eg iTerm2), El Capitan style
3. Quit Code

Crash reporter comes up. Couldn't repro with barebones Electron.

- type a + b + space
  Observe: an internal error occurs:
  ![2016-01-26 13-05-31](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1898161/12580180/a7ff6b46-c42d-11e5-9d74-0a6163ca47b7.png)

If the crash doesn't occur immediately, just keep typing...

The node debugger in VS Code seems to die after the first console.log output. While I am not 100% sure this is the actual problem, I don't recall ever having a problem until I upgraded to Node 4.2.6 (current LTS version).

No output, no warnings. VS Code itself does not crash.

If there is a log I can reference to help with this issue report, I am happy to look if given some instructions on how to find it.

For what it's worth, outside this issue, VS Code is hands down the best node debugger tool I have used.

VSCode doesn't start up with a console. However, I often start it from powershell with `start code .` instead of just `code .` (Since occasionally VSCode ends up dumping data into a console that I'm using for something else, and starting with the latter doesn't truly isolate the process, it rather just runs the message loop still connected to the same console).

- VSCode Version: 0.10.12-alpha
- OS Version: MAC OS X EI captian (Version 10.11.2)

Steps to Reproduce:
1.  launch app and play around help menu to make application to be crashed (current behavior) or try to perform any action which makes VSCode to be crashed on MAC.
2. Once you get the alert window for crash click on "Reopen" button and verify application behavior.

Actual: 
1. VSCode re-launched successfully but it is not displaying in the active program list at the bottom right corner where all the active programs are listed.
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/17735796/13892695/5bb66534-ed16-11e5-8756-78ae41f72e50.png)
1. Menu bar at the top is not changing according to VSCode so MAC is unable to recognize VSCode active session. Menu bar items are displaying for the last active window though the focus is on VScode. In my case it was "Safari".
   Note: I am not certain if this is the common behavior on MAC for crashed app.

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/17735796/13892624/e44c1f0c-ed15-11e5-9ee9-3a07fb016b82.png)
3. When I try to uninstall app, it is keep throwing pop-up that the app is running and can't trash. But there is no active session anywhere. I observed that the app stuck with Finder and user has to forcefully close finder first. After forcefully closing finder and re-launching VSCode , it is working as expected.

- VSCode Version: 0.10.11
- OS Version: Win 10

Steps to Reproduce:
1. Open folder containing this file: https://github.com/kjur/jsrsasign/blob/master/npm/lib/jsrsasign.js
2. Open file and scroll around a bit. VS Code gets really slow/laggy.

Hi *,

I try to replace webstorm with vscode as my main development editor/IDE, but as of now its not possible for me. Im not sure if this is a bug or misconfiguration of my system but IntelliSense, "Go to definition" and other useful stuff don't work for JavaScript or TypeScript files. On the other hand "context-aware" JSONs like `tsconfig.json`, `package.json` do work like expected.

This is my test repo: https://github.com/otbe/vscode-intellisense-test

And this happens on my (and only on my) machine:
![no-intellisense](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/3391052/14424337/d419dbc8-ffe0-11e5-9539-b8cd4f0b3828.gif)

I have made no changes to the default settings of vscode.

Grateful for every hint :/
Thanks.

Versions:
- VSCode Version: 0.10.14-insider | 0.10.11
- OS Version: OS X 10.11.3

**Performance issue**:

`glob.match('**/bower.json',...)` results in:
 `/^(?:[\/\\]|[^\/\\]+[\/\\]|[\/\\][^\/\\]+)*?bower\.json$/`  which looks rather complicated.
It seems to work but runs in a timeout on a long content (I tried with the default content of http://regexr.com/)

So its a ('separator' or 'everything but a separator followed by a separator' or a 'separator followed by a everything but a separator') repeated and optional. A very complicated way of saying  /bower.json$/ 

**Updated comment from #6936**:

Then there other cases that are still far too complicated and inefficient. It looks like #5438 is not really fixed.
{**/*.ts,**/_.tsx__/_.js,**/*.jsx,**/_.es6} ->
(?:(?:[/\]._?|.+?[/\]|)[^/\]_?.ts|(?:[/\]._?|.+?[/\]|)[^/\]_?.ts|(?:[/\]._?|.+?[/\]|)[^/\]_?.tsx[^/\]_?[^/\]_?[/\][^/\]_?.js|(?:[/\]._?|.+?[/\]|)[^/\]_?.jsx|(?:[/\]._?|.+?[/\]|)[^/\]_?.es6)
It's correct, but `*.\.ts|*.\.tsx|*.\.js|*.\.tsx` would do it. The non-capturing groups also don't seem to be needed.

**Wrong results in some cases**:
`glob.match("**/project.json",...)` results in the regexp `(?:[/\\].*?|.+?[/\\]|)project\.json`

The or segment is strange `[/\\].*?`.
This results in `/rrproject.json` to be matched

**Updated comment from #19926**:
`server/**/**.js` should not match `server.js`

That allows rapid switching between workspaces and is now gone...

- VSCode Version: 1.1.1
- OS Version: Windows 10 Pro x64

Steps to Reproduce:
1. Create a  `TypeScript` project with the following structure : 
   `tsconfig.json`
   `app/`
   `app/application.ts`
   `app/framework/`
   `app/framework/application.ts (included in application.ts)`
   `app/framework/some other typescripts files (included in framework/application.ts)`
   `app/appNameHere/`
   `app/appNameHere/application.ts (included in application.ts)`
   `app/appNameHere/some other typescripts files (included in appNameHere/application.ts)`
   
   So basically : 
   - `app/application.ts` will only contain references to `framework/application.ts` and `appNameHere/application.ts`.
   - `app/framework/application.ts` will only contain references to files from `framework` folder.
   - `app/appNameHere/application.ts` will only contain references to files from `appNameHere` folder.
2. Create a `tsconfig.json` as follow : 
   `{
   "compileOnSave": true,
   "compilerOptions": {
       "target": "es5",
       "removeComments": true,
       "outFile": "application.js",
       "sourceMap": true,
       "noImplicitAny": true
   },
   "files": [
       "app/application.ts"
   ]
   }`
3. Add some TS files in both directory and play with it, try using intellisense of a class from another file
4. Up at some point, TypeScript intellisense seems to crash and to get it again, we need to restart vscode

The Intellisense is crashing a lot in one day on my side with that settings at my job, it will say it doesn't know what is a class that should be defined, until you restart vscode ...

If you need more informations, I'll be glad to offer them. However, I am not in the ability to share my projet as it is confidential files from my job.

- VSCode Version: Code 1.4.0 (6276dcb0ae497766056b4c09ea75be1d76a8b679, 2016-08-04T16:41:29.513Z)
- OS Version: Darwin x64 14.5.0

Steps to Reproduce:

1.Connect to a network drive using SMB or AFP
2.Open a file on one of those drives in VSCode
3.Disconnect the drive.
4.VSCode crashes

Sublime does NOT behave this way. 

Here's why it is a problem... I'm working on a set of files on a network drive. I move my laptop to a different location, or switch from wired to wireless. The network drive disconnects. Now, I lose all the files I was working on and have to re-open them all. 

Another example...  I'm working on 10+ files at the end of the day and I close my laptop and go home. The next morning I come in, and I have to re-open all 10 of those files (assuming I remember what they were).

Correct behavior should be to keep the file open.  Of course, you can't save it until you reconnect the network drives, but at least it is there.  This is how Sublime works.

I'm not sure how to reproduce this; if I manage to do it again, I'll update the issue. 
I was seeing high (~97-100%) CPU usage from this `Code Helper.app` process running `tsserver.js`:
```
/Users/jskrzypek/Downloads/Visual Studio Code.app/Contents/Frameworks/Code Helper.app/Contents/MacOS/Code Helper /Users/jskrzypek/Downloads/Visual Studio Code.app/Contents/Resources/app/extensions/typescript/out/utils/electronForkStart /usr/local/lib/node_modules/typescript/lib/tsserver.js --useSingleInferredProject --enableTelemetry
```
I noticed that both this process and another Code Helper running `typescript`
```
/Users/jskrzypek/Downloads/Visual Studio Code.app/Contents/Frameworks/Code Helper.app/Contents/MacOS/Code Helper /Users/jskrzypek/.nvm/versions/node/v6.9.5/lib/node_modules/typescript/lib/typingsInstaller.js --globalTypingsCacheLocation /Users/jskrzypek/Library/Caches/typescript --enableTelemetry
```
stuck around after quitting vscode. I googled for an issue and found #20260 which had an instruction to try using the `TSS_LOG` shell parameter to enable tsserver logging. I "force quit" the misbehaving `tsserver.js` activity from the Activity Monitor and then followed the instructions in the comment https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/issues/20260#issuecomment-282408109 and ran this:
```
export TSS_LOG="-level verbose -file ~/tss.log"
code .
```
After vscode opened, I got a warning at the top of the window informing me that the typescript service had died repeatedly more than 5 times in the last 5 minutes. This warning modal kept appearing repeatedly, leading me to believe that whatever was triggering the warning kept occurring. I clicked on the button to create the issue and then quit vscode. When I looked, the `tts.log` file did not  exist. After running `code .` a second time the warning did not appear.

Other notes:

It noticed that I also have a Sublime Text node process running `tsserver.js` hanging around long after I've quit ST that is also showing high cpu use. I was running bot ST and vscode simultaneously at some point recently, I think on the same project/folder.

We see traces in which Electron takes a very long time to to receive the `app-ready` event. Because we cannot do anything useful before that happens it blocks startup badly. AV software is suspected to be causing this.

Per discussion here: https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/issues/18055

Some things I noticed while looking into this:
* I believe either `--max_old_space_size` or `--max-old-space-size` works, v8 args can be dashes or underscores. Underscores work for sure.
* TSServer appears to have special logic if `global.gc` is available, so maybe consider adding `--expose-gc` as well.
* I believe the maximum settings for 64-bit builds of Node is `4096`
* There's this: https://github.com/electron/electron/issues/9693. Essentially when running VS Code with the `./script/code.sh` script, setting these flags in `execArgv` options in `typescriptserviceclient.ts` had no effect. ~I think it'll work if Electron is packaged and ran normally, but I'm not positive.~

This one is quite tough. 
Today it was almost impossible for me to use the integrated terminal and build tasks in VSCode. Some tools occasionally crashed when they were run inside the integrated terminal. The tools randomly stopped writing their output while some others aborted with a "Disk full" error. This happened everytime when the tools were writing a lot of output to the integrated terminal.
I tested them intensively in standalone powershell and cmd windows: They worked as expected. They only crashed when running inside the integrated terminal.

My first thought was that it had something to do with the latest update of VSCode so I downgraded to the September release but it showed the same odd behaviour.

Then I uninstalled the Windows 10 Fall Creators Update which I installed last night. Now everything works fine again.

I guess this is more an issue in Windows than in VSCode but it's quite strange that different applications crash only when they run in the integrated terminal. That's why I post it here. Maybe you have an idea what could have changed in the Windows API that causes this effect. And I guess you might be interested in having applications behave identically regardless the terminal in which they are being run.

I've managed to create a test project that (almost) always crashed when running in the integrated terminal. It will print 100k lines of output to the terminal. You can find it here: https://github.com/Wosi/Print100kLines

Steps to reproduce (hopefully):
  - Install VSCode to a Windows 10 machine with the Fall Creator's Update
  - Run Print100kLines.exe in the integrated terminal -> It crashed on my system
  - Run the same application in any other terminal and it will work fine

- VSCode Version: 1.21.0
- OS Version: Antergos, current today
- Video Driver: Nvidia 390.25

Steps to Reproduce:

1. Install arch linux (or antergos) current version
2. Install Nvidia 384+ version for an Nvidia video card (10 series)
3. Install vscode from git repository current version
4. Randomly it will trigger the X server to crash and drop you back to login screen

Fix is to update package.json from electron 1.7.7 to current 1.8.3. I removed the AUR package version and manually installed from the git repository and updated the electron version in package.json and the problem seems to have disappeared.

<!-- Launch with `code --disable-extensions` to check. -->
Does this issue occur when all extensions are disabled?: Yes

This problem has been plaguing VScode for maybe 3 version increments, and it's caused by using an old version of electron.

- VSCode Version: 1.22.1
- OS Version: Windows 10 

Steps to Reproduce:

1. clone the following repo and navigate to the test>back-end>routes.test.js file: 
```git clone https://github.com/RonanQuigley/vscode-intellisense-bug .```
2. run ```yarn``` to install the node_modules folder. You do not need to execute any script to see this problem.
3. Adjust the import path as demonstrated in the gif below. Notice that aside from being slow (around 1s to update a path, intellisense eventually hangs on 'Loading...' and won't work without an update. 

![intellisense](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/33596237/38423785-d30fd9f6-39a6-11e8-8d72-e545146c45bf.gif)

I've tried to replicate this with a barebones project i.e. just two files but it never happens. I've also managed to narrow it down to the node_modules folder. Intellisense, when scanning that folder, will crash if the project has a lot of modules. Just before the crash I've consistently have had this sort of cpu spike:

![spike](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/33596237/38424864-49908848-39aa-11e8-8913-0bf29579ddc9.PNG)

If you delete the node modules folder, the issue is gone. If you reduce the number of modules, whilst intellisense is a bit slower, the issue is also gone. If you use require instead of import, the issue is also there. I tried to see if it was a specific module causing it, but my tests have shown that it's not the case. It's just the sheer number of modules being used. 

Is there intellisense logging that I can provide that would help? The only current workaround is to restart vscode, which if like me, you encounter this issue incessantly is a complete pain in the butt to deal with. 

There's loads of other files in this project; I've just left them in in case there's something contributing to the issue that perhaps I'm missing. So whilst I have tried to minimise the project to the least amount of files, it only happens in larger setups unfortunately.

Does this issue occur when all extensions are disabled?: Yes

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/900690/38548862-1d59a456-3cb3-11e8-91a8-a13175d6d591.png)


Extensions in VS Code are running in a node.js process. When we update to version 8.x of node.js, the node module ["natives"](https://www.npmjs.com/package/natives) is no longer supported by node.js. It actually never was officially supported but with node.js 8.x using this module can result in a crash that brings down the entire extension host. 

**As such, VS Code will prevent loading this module.**

If you see an extension failing due to this, please reach out to the extension author and ask to update the dependencies so that the `"natives"` module is no longer required. You can find the contact details of an extension in the right sidebar of the [marketplace](https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/vscode):

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/900690/38548810-fad24d7a-3cb2-11e8-83e6-b86db9a759e0.png)

Put simply: VS Code does not handle network interruptions well enough.

### Here's what leads to problems:
Work within a single folder
Folder is hosted on a server (network volume on macOS, ie. smb://)
Volume is only accessible once connected through a VPN (built-in to macOS)
Use VS Code to edit files in this volume folder.
Disconnect from wifi, put the computer to sleep, or disconnect from a VPN.

### Here's the problem:
Whenever the VPN (or any internet connection, really) is disconnected, VS Code turns into an unresponsive mess. Laggy, whole thing locks up. After 5 minutes, when it's figured itself out, VS Code is now much slower, and FILLED with like 57 error messages about how it couldn't find the files... of course the open files don't exist, I'm not connected to the Volume! 

### What I expect to happen:
Once internet/VPN is disconnected, **DON'T freak out**; **don't crash**, **don't lock up** and become laggy, **don't show me a single error message**. Just handle it all in the background, nicely, like the rest of macOS applications do: just keep the files open and re-sync everything once re-connected. Until then, just hang tight and let me edit my opened files. The **ONLY** error message displayed should be whenever I try to save a file; obviously you can't save a file to a location that isn't connected.

It's causing a huge amount of frustration and extra effort spent babysitting VS Code for us, when it can all be handled quietly in the background. Again, it's EXPECTED for all these files to "go missing" as the user moves from different WiFi connections, disconnects from VPNs, and puts the computer to sleep (turning off WiFi temporarily).

<!-- Use Help > Report Issue to prefill these. -->
- VSCode Version: 1.30.1
- OS Version: ubuntu 18.10

Steps to Reproduce:
 
1. when i use gdb debug, it crashed. the error message is : stopping due to fatal error: NullReferenceException: Object reference not set 

<!-- Launch with `code --disable-extensions` to check. -->
Does this issue occur when all extensions are disabled?: Yes

## Environment
- VSCode Version: 1.30.0 (installed from official MS repo)
- OS Version: Fedora Workstation 29

## Problem
OpenSSL version shipped with Fedora 29 seems to be incompatible with what VSCode expects.

Error I've got while trying to install Python Language Server:

```
Downloading https://pvsc.azureedge.net/python-language-server-stable/Python-Language-Server-linux-x64.0.1.72.nupkg... complete.
Unpacking archive... done.
No usable version of the libssl was found
[Info  - 10:14:55] Connection to server got closed. Server will restart.
No usable version of the libssl was found
[Info  - 10:14:58] Connection to server got closed. Server will restart.
No usable version of the libssl was found
[Info  - 10:15:00] Connection to server got closed. Server will restart.
No usable version of the libssl was found
[Info  - 10:15:02] Connection to server got closed. Server will restart.
No usable version of the libssl was found
[Error - 10:15:04] Connection to server got closed. Server will not be restarted.
```

## Workaround
 I found [similar issue on Live-Share repo](https://github.com/MicrosoftDocs/live-share/issues/1385), workaround found there was to install compat lib:

```
sudo dnf install compat-openssl10
```

It solves the problem with VSCode as well.

## Possible solution
Add `compat-openssl10` to dependencies list, or upgrade openssl version used by VSCode.

Hello, 
I am seeing a crash when debugging my program within vscode. The crash doesn't happen if debugging outside of vscode or run from the terminal directly.

I am running the 'snap' vscode under Ubuntu 18.10 with default "unity" look window manager.

To reproduce this you will need the "cmake-tools-helper" extension installed because the build uses cmake. I have cmake 3.12.1 installed.  I don't believe the issue I am seeing is with the extensions I am using because I can build the program executable with vscode using these extensions and then run that same program outside of vscode without a problem.

You will need to install wxwidgets development libraries because the program uses wxwidgets. Note that wxwidgets libraries are also linked against libpng. 

Pre-requisites: 

Install wxwidgets and cmake from terminal:

sudo apt-get install g++
sudo apt-get install cmake
sudo apt-get install libwxgtk3.0-dev

Steps to reproduce:
1. Run vscode from terminal. I am running as a normal user which can be elevated with "sudo" to install packages.
2. Inside vscode use "open folder" and choose the folder where the CMakeLists.txt file is located for the program. See attached "minexp.zip"
3. Click on the cmake triangle icon on the bar on the left to access the cmake tools.
4. Click on the configure button/cmake smaller triangle at the top of the cmake tool window. Use gcc 6.5.0 if prompted. I tried clang with the same results. You need a compiler that can build programs. The cmake tools will fail to configure if you don't have one of those.
Check configuration is successful in the output window.
5. Click on the hammer button at the top of the cmake tool window. The code will build.
6. Check build is successful.
7. Check "export" program executable has been built inside the build folder which is located within the source directory.
8. "Start Debugging" in vscode to debug the executable. I see gdb outputting logging. If it breaks at the start of the program "go" to make it run. You will see a dialog appear with a title and a menu. This is the program running.
9. Click on the window and attempt to use the file menu.
You will get see a crash in memcpy-sse3. In the callstack libpng is mentioned. It is not possible to skip this and continue. 
10. In a terminal go to the executable's location and run it and do the same as before. NOTE: It will not crash.
11. In a terminal go to the executable's location run it via gdb and do the same as before. (gdb export, run). NOTE: it will not crash.

My expectation is that I can use the debugger in vscode and that it is consistent with running from the terminal or via gdb in the terminal in that the operation is the same, currently vscode is inconsistent with the other methods to run it.

I checked that the paths that the gdb launched from the terminal and the gdb launched by vscode were using for the shared libraries that were loaded. I saw they were the same. Kevin

<!-- Describe the feature you'd like. -->
Use-case: microservices development. day 2 maintenance scenario support. Crash and customer issues analyzes caused by  bugs in implementation of microservice already deployed to cloud infrastructure. 
Expected capability: create duplicate container instance available for analyzes, debugging and correction without temporary denial user from service via creating separate container instance  available to developer only. Developer can modify state of such container without service denial.
Reference capabilities:
Microsoft Azure Snapshot debugger and Google StackDriver debugger
Technical barrier:
developer can't attach debugger to stopped or crashed container used by microservice user because afinity mechanism will require transfer afinity cookies from user to another person which is strictly prohibited from security point-of-view. 
Feature is supported by Cloud infrastructures: Azure & Kubernetes via public API.
Preliminary efforts estimations:
UI extension - small
DAP protocol extension - small
Debug adapter implementation extension - large

Steps to Reproduce: 1. Run a python file using command palette >Python: Run file in terminal window 2. Terminal shows the output. Now, clear the terminal using command palette >Terminal: Clear 3. Terminal gets clear now. Run the file again in the terminal >Python: Run file in terminal window 4. Here is where issue shows up - the terminal still shows all the previous outputs from before the last clear command. IMO, desired should be that terminal should not show any previously cleared outputs. 5. Issue Type: Bug **Reproduction:** - Open vscode. - Leave it in the background for some time. - Try to switch back to vscode. **Expected result:** - vscode gets displayed and can be manipulated. **Actual result:** - the vscode window is frozen, doesn't refresh, and shows the last open app (or desktop background, ... [HockeyApp will be shut down](https://www.hockeyapp.net/blog/2018/11/16/thanks-hockeyapp-app-center-will-take-it-from-here.html) on (after?) November 16, 2019, so it would probably be a good idea to migrate crash reporting to a different service soon.

Theoretically, something called "App Center" is supposed to be taking over HockeyApp's responsibilities, but since the [Windows Transition Plan](https://github.com/microsoft/appcenter/blob/specs/specs/2019-04/Windows-Plan.md) indicates that they neither know of Win32 support in HockeyApp nor have any immediate plans to add any to App Center, I doubt if that's actually the best option here.

Starting from electron's [crashReporter](https://electronjs.org/docs/api/crash-reporter>) docs, and cross-referencing with [Crashpad overview design](https://chromium.googlesource.com/crashpad/crashpad/+/HEAD/doc/overview_design.md) (since Electron uses crashpad for Mac), it looks like breakpad protocol is used in all cases.

You could self-host:

* [mini-breakpad-server](https://github.com/electron/mini-breakpad-server)
* [Sentry](https://docs.sentry.io/server/) 
* [socorro](https://github.com/mozilla/socorro) if you're feeling adventurous

Or use a 3rd party hosted solution:

* [Backtrace](https://backtrace.io/electron/)
* [Sentry](https://docs.sentry.io/clients/electron)
* [BugSplat](https://www.bugsplat.com/docs/platforms/electron)

(I may have copied and pasted most of these bullets from the markdown source of https://electronjs.org/docs/api/crash-reporter.)

I guess you'd also want to rename the `hockeyApp` property in [`poduct.ts`](https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/blob/master/src/vs/platform/product/node/product.ts)/`product.json` to something more generic.

3. Launch VSCode from either command line or Start Menu
4. Close VSCode

I've been using VSCode for FE development (Angular, Vue) for quite some time without any problems. A while ago I started using it also for Java by installing the Java Extension Pack and created a workspace with 1 Angular project and 2 Java projects. Everything worked quite well, but I noticed, that after closing VSCode some of my other applications (Chrome, Firefox, Slack) became unresponsive. To get them running again I hat to restart my computer. Last week I had to switch to a different project (workspace) and noticed a similar behavior -> this time VSCode froze and became unresponsive together with the rest of the apps. I suspected the Java extensions (as it was working fine before) and tried to resolve the problem by uninstalling/deactivating all extensions (not only the Java ones), followed by a complete re-install of VSCode. I also deactivated automatic updates of VSCode and all the extensions. Nothing helped and so I removed all extensions and tried to run VSCode with various command-line parameters, but this also did not resolve the problems. Running VSCode with "--verbose --disable-extensions --disable-gpu" I was able to successfully switch folders 2 times, but after that the problem re-occurred again. I did not find any pattern in the behavior... sometimes I can do 1 successful folder switch/open, but most of the time it hangs after the first switch/open. The strange thing is that "apps without network connection" like Total Commander, cmd, PowerShell, Notepad++ still work correctly after VSCode hangs... this bug only seems to affect apps using some kind of network connection?

Is there anything else I could try? Does it make sense to try a previous/different version of VSCode to ensure this was not introduced in one of the latest updates? Thanks a lot for any kind of ideas/help in advance.

Issue Type: Performance Issue I am working in a large codebase. I am turning on a TSLint Rule (no-floating-promises) and going through each file one-by-one and fixing it manually. I am doing this by pasting in some text (`trackBackgroundTask(` followed by a `)` a few lines later to wrap the offending code). As I do this pasting, the whole UX becomes unresponsive for a second or up to three. The first time I paste within a file it is responsive for a moment but then not responsive for a couple seconds while it is likely analyzing the file for other errors and TSLint warnings; I say "likely" because the UX becomes interactive again at the same time that highlighting in the file is updated. This unresponsiveness gets in the way because I often know where I want my cursor to go but I cannot place it there until the UX is responsive. It would be much better if I could always navigate freely and that file analysis always happened in the background in a non-clocking fashion. Recently VS Code started crashing at every startup on my job laptop. I uninstalled, reinstalled, tried insiders and so on, but nothing helped. I even tried building from source to debug (but failed) but eventually windbg gave me a clue: the process dies before it even reaches main. I finally tried just disabling "Host IPS" ("McAfee Host Intrusion Prevention for Desktop") and suddenly vs code works.

What is doubly puzzling is that my computer is the only one doing this but mcafee is running on every computer and others can start vs code! I dont know if this means mcafee has some adaptive, per-user behaviour.

I realize this might be hard for you guys to do anything about, but at least this might help someone else with the same problem, tried finding anything about this came up empty.

I can reproduce both with Electron 4 and Electron 6.
Create ps1 script using Az cmdlet, e.g Get-AzKeyVaultSecret, and run the script from the integrated terminal.  Observe the console dies.

* this is only possible once we adopt Electron 6, in Electron 4 we get the error `Cannot initialize out-of-process crash handler` on Windows.
  * This is possible in Electron 6 because it has adopted crashpad for crash reporting on windows, which aligns with what Chromium was doing.
* this can be implemented easily by defining the crash reporter options for the extension host [here](https://github.com/microsoft/vscode/blob/9b0b5968ad18afe511bde480b6dfb04e48ebc377/src/vs/workbench/services/extensions/electron-browser/extensionHost.ts#L165)

Issue Type: Bug 1. Install latest insider build of VS Code 2. Install Debugger for Chrome extension 3. `git clone https://github.com/justingrant/repro-debug-scripts-hang.git` This is a brand-new create-react-app repo with a few lines of code that pull in lots of dependencies to simulate a real app. 4. `yarn` 5. `yarn start` 6. start IDE debugger (using Chrome debug config in the repo) 7. In debug console pane, enter `.scripts`, then press ESC (to avoid the bad auto-completions), and then press ENTER. The IDE will take a 3-5 seconds to emit ~1600 lines (which seems reasonable given the number of files it has to process) but after the lines are emitted is when the problem happens. Expected: VSCode is responsive after `.scripts` is done executing Actual: VSCode is completely unresponsive (no cursor blinking, no response to mouse clicks) for 10-20 seconds. Afterwards, responsiveness comes back, but if you resize the VSCode window, or switch to the terminal pane and then back to the debug console pane, the IDE is yet again unresponsive for 10-20 seconds. The repro above describes behavior from from the latest insiders build, but I originally encountered this problem with the latest non-insiders build (1.39.2), and on non-insider build it was even worse: the IDE never comes back to responsiveness-- instead a crash report is generated and you need to close the window before you can use it again. Issue Type: Bug 1) Make sure the extension "Azure Resource Manager Tools" is installed (this bug only repros when the arm-expression-string.tmLanguage.json grammar from this extension is installed) 2) New file 3) copy the following string into this file: ``` " \"xmlCfg\": \"[base64(' ')]\"," ``` 4) Set the language to Azure Resource Manager Template !) vscode hangs NOTE: This code is *not* a normal string to have in an ARM template file. Rather, it's from a snippet for such files (i.e., it's encoded an extra time). I found this scenario by accidentally setting the language to arm-template while I had the snippet file open. I haven't heard of any customers hitting this yet, so I'll let you guys decide on the priority. I tried to narrow down the string further, but the repro became inconsistent at that point. Steps to Reproduce:

1. "F1 -> Specify jupyter server URI"
2. "http://****/?token=***", the link to the remote jupyter server.
3. open a ".py" file including some "#%%" cells and click "Run Cell"

- VSCode Version: 1.40.2 / Insiders: 1.41.0
- OS Version: Windows 7 (Also reproduced on Windows 10 and Fedora)

Steps to Reproduce:

1. Open or Create a new typescript project.  The bigger the better.  A new angular project should suffice.
2. Open taskmanager to monitor process ram usage.  Take note of current RAM usage of process for tsserver.js
3. Open a .ts file and type slowly.  Make mistakes.  Note that the RAM usage of tsserver.js increases (the bigger the project the faster it will increase).  Note that the RAM usage never decreases even if you leave it running for a long time.
4. At some point (I havn't been able to figure out what triggers this), it will suddenly balloon up in memory usage until it hits the maximum available RAM on the system.  It will ignore the max_old_space_size setting.  e.g. In my case whether I set it to 3072 or 300 when this issue happens it will rapidly use up 20.5Gb of RAM and 100% of a cpu core.

<!-- Launch with `code --disable-extensions` to check. -->
Does this issue occur when all extensions are disabled?: No, requires the TSLint extension (tested with v1.2.3)

Additional Notes:
Both regular and insiders editions have this issue.
VSCode 1.39.2 appears to be working correctly, I've been unable to reproduce.  RAM usage will increase but never shoots up so rapidly and if left alone for a few seconds the GC will kick in and usage drops drastically.

It appears these issues might be related: 
#84326 - note the 98% RAM usage in screenshot)
#84585 - Complaints about RAM, CPU and unresponsive autocompletion
There are a number of other issues mentioning VSCode being "slow" in the last few weeks which leads me to believe this issue is affecting quite a few devs.

**Steps to Reproduce:**

1. Create new folder and create new python virtual environment `venv`. 
2. activate `venv`
3. `pip install pyzmq`  (Using version 18.1.1)
4. Copy paste the following code in a file and run

```
# echoClient.py
import sys
import time
import zmq

if __name__ == "__main__":
    if len(sys.argv) != 2:
        sys.stderr.write("Add port as argument")
        sys.exit(1)

    context = zmq.Context()
    socket = context.socket(zmq.REQ)
    socket.connect("tcp://localhost:%d" % int(sys.argv[1]))
    socket.setsockopt(zmq.LINGER, 0)

    print("Sending ...")
    times = 0
    while True:
        times += 1
        msg = "Message".encode('utf-8')
        send_OK = socket.poll(1, zmq.POLLOUT)
        socket.send(msg)   # <-- Will crash here if Server is not connected
        #  Get the reply.

        if socket.poll(10, zmq.POLLIN):
            message_recd = socket.recv()
            print("Received %s" % message_recd)

            if msg == message_recd:
                print("ECHO OK")
            
            else:
                print("ECHO NOT OK")

        else:
            print("Timeout")
        
        time.sleep(1)   

    # close socket and exit
    socket.close()
    context.term()
```

This code will crash if a listener is not connected because of the internal state machine mechanisms of a zmq REQ socket, that is you cannot send() twice without recv() after every send().

The issue is that VSCode seems to look for the exception information in `.\zmq\backend\cython\checkrc.pxd` when it should be looking in the site-packages folder. The correct path is `.\venv\Lib\site-packages\zmq\backend\cython\checkrc.pxd`

**Error message** - Unable to open 'checkrc.pxd': Unable to read file (Error: File not found (c:\pyprojects\echoclient\zmq\backend\cython\checkrc.pxd)).

<!-- Launch with `code --disable-extensions` to check. -->
Does this issue occur when all extensions are disabled?: Yes

The worker_thread API is available, but attempting to use it in an extension crashes VS Code.

1. Create a "hello world" extension from a template
2. Create a blank worker.js file
3. Add this to your extension's activate:

```js
const { Worker } = require('worker_threads');
new Worker(join(__dirname, 'worker.js'));
```

nbconvert cant run this ipynb file.

Does this issue occur when all extensions are disabled?:
I cannot try without SSH extension currently (but this should not be relevant).

I think the issue is that the directory is just very big.

I happened already multiple times that the Linux server became unresponsive because all memory was occupied, and luckily the Linux OOM killer killed `rg` and the system recovered a while later. This is what I see in `dmesg -T`:

```
# pytorch
trans = transforms.Compose([transforms.ToTensor(), normalize])
```
and then i use trans, 
```
c_tensor = trans(c)
```

- VSCode Version: 1.45.0
- OS Version: macOS Catalina

I use vscode to write and debug python scrapy (webcrawler) code. Sometimes the debugger messes up totally. Running lines of code one or two steps later or crash the python interpreter with errors that make no sense at all.

The interesting thing is that if i use `print("foo")` the debugger works fine again. If I remove the print() the debugger messes up again.
Im not 100 per cent sure that this issue is vscode related but maybe my wrong implementation of code.

Is there a way to get vscode to "cleanup" the debugger? Quitting vscode or restarting the computer does not work.

- VSCode Version: 1.47.0, 1.48.0-insider
- OS Version: macOS 10.15.5
- Remote SSH: Ubuntu 18.04

Steps to Reproduce:

1. Install vscode-R extension.
2. Set `r.sessionWatcher` to `true`, and reload vscode.
3. Use Remote-SSH to connect to remote Linux server (where R is installed).
4. Install vscode-R extension to remote server.
5. `Create R terminal` and an R session is started
6. Run `?get`

It starts an http server that provides the R documentation, and a VSCode
WebView should show up by the following extension code. 

```typescript
function showBrowser(url: string, title: string, viewer: string | boolean) {
    console.info(`[showBrowser] uri: ${url}, viewer: ${viewer}`);
    if (viewer === false) {
        env.openExternal(Uri.parse(url));
    } else {
        const port = parseInt(new URL(url).port);
        const panel = window.createWebviewPanel(
            'browser',
            title,
            {
                preserveFocus: true,
                viewColumn: ViewColumn[String(viewer)],
            },
            {
                enableScripts: true,
                retainContextWhenHidden: true,
                portMapping: [
                    {
                        extensionHostPort: port,
                        webviewPort: port,
                    },
                ],
            });
        panel.webview.html = getBrowserHtml(url);
    }
    console.info('[showBrowser] Done');
}

function getBrowserHtml(url: string) {
    return `
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
  <style>
    html, body {
        height: 100%;
        padding: 0;
        overflow: hidden;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
    <iframe src="${url}" width="100%" height="100%" frameborder="0" />
</body>
</html>
`;
}
```

When `viewer="Active"`, the WebView cannot be shown properly with the latest release and insider of VSCode. The `iframe` content is empty.

```html
<iframe src="http://127.0.0.1:22784/library/base/html/get.html" width="100%" height="100%" frameborder="0">
</body>
</html>
</iframe>
```

However, if I run the following in R

```r
.vsc.browser("http://127.0.0.1:22784/library/base/html/get.html", viewer = FALSE)
```

which basically calls `showBrowser` with `viewer=false`, then a local web browser is open by `env.openExternal(Uri.parse(url));` the web page is properly shown. Only after this, I call `?get`, or equivalently

```r
.vsc.browser("http://127.0.0.1:22784/library/base/html/get.html", viewer = "Active")
```

The WebView could be properly shown.

I guess the port mapping of WebView via Remote SSH somehow is not working and it works with the port mapping enabled by `env.openExternal(Uri.parse(url))`. Everything works well if the same is done locally.

Related: https://github.com/Ikuyadeu/vscode-R/issues/380.

Issue Type: Bug This was previously reported on the orca list and appears to be related to the upgrade to electron 9. Steps: 1. Launch orca. 1. turn on Speak indentation and justification in the tab speech of orca's preferences page. 1. Open an empty file in VSCode. 1. Press the tab and type this is a test. 1. Press the enter key. 1. Browse the text using up and down arrow. Orca reads the text preceded by the number of leading spaces in the line, as expected. 1. Convert the indentation to tabs. 1. Browse the text using up and down arrow. Orca should read the text preceded by the number of initial tabs in the line but instead it announces that there is a space at the beginning of the line. On the orca list @joanie commented the following: >This commit fixes the problem -- though it's not a specific fix for >it: https://chromium.googlesource.com/chromium/src/+/e49659287. Not >sure if it should be cherry-picked into Electron 9 or not.... **Steps to Reproduce:** The issue occurs highly sporadically and could not yet be reproduced. It occurs very seldomly, but when it occurs, it can be extremely annoying. When it occurs, there will appear some random tooltip with the default Electron design somewhere on the screen. If you go through all your open VS Code windows, maybe you are lucky and find the source of the tooltip. By hovering that widget again, the tooltip is finally destroyed. To illustrate, in my example, one tooltip said "20 Errors".

From what we know, the issue is connected to the use of touchscreens on Windows.

The same problem was already reported for Chromium here: <https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1052238#makechanges>. I have no clue of Electron development, but there is any common denominator with Chromium, isn't it?

Steps to Reproduce:

1. I have the following code in a Python module called `temp.py`:
```
import numpy as np

a = np.arange(1, 5)
b = np.arange(-1, 7)
c = np.arange(3, 10)
d = np.arange(11, 17)

np.savez("temp", a=a, b=b, c=c, d=d, name="name", verbose=True)
with np.load("temp.npz") as data:
    print(data)
    print(data["name"])
    print(type(data["name"]))
    pass
```
2. I have a breakpoint on the `pass` statement
3. I launch the debugger using the "Python: current file" option
4. After reaching the breakpoint, in the debug console, I enter `data["name"]`, which returns the output `array('name', dtype='<U4')`
5. I click on the arrow to expand the attributes of this object, and then the debugger crashes, with the error message `Server[1] disconnected unexpectedly`

I'm using Python 3.7.6, Numpy version 1.18.1.

Issue Type: Bug Open a Java .properties file (for example the application.properties of a Spring Boot application) which contains a hash character in the middle of the line (not as the first character), for example "spring.output.ansi.enabled=ALWAYS # Invalid comment" Note that this ITS does not support .properties files. This can be seen at line 28 in the following screenshot, where "Journaliser en couleur" is an invalid comment which should be on its own line: ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/486141/94321503-b318a680-ff5d-11ea-96af-a8dfcc1a7839.png) As [explained on Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/.properties), comments in .properties files need to be on their own line. No clear steps to reproduce. I do use PlatformIO constantly, which every now and then (quite often) just no longer responds and sometimes VScode is showing a notification telling me the extension host has stopped.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/3751318/94446280-b5bb0c00-01a8-11eb-8896-5942d501fce4.png)

<!-- Launch with `code --disable-extensions` to check. -->
Does this issue occur when all extensions are disabled?: Yes/No
Not tested as I can't work in VScode without PlatformIO, but have disabled some of the other extensions, which doesn't seem to make a difference.

For completeness, these are the installed extensions:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/3751318/94446375-d84d2500-01a8-11eb-95ca-08de999a23fc.png)

N.B. the logs suggest memory allocation issues, but that's probably some configured limit or some internal 32 bit limit as my system does have lots and lots of free memory right now. (currently only 13GB in use of the 96GB)

Issue Type: Bug The unicode point U+200C (ZERO_WIDTH_NON_JOINER) can be inserted between to characters to prevent ligatures. That normally works everywhere else. But it doesn't work in Visual Studio Code. I created a code file to see the effect of ligatures on certain code snippets. I put the non-ligatures in comments directly after it. In Visual Studio Code the characters spereated by the ZERO_WIDTH_NON_JOINER are still shown as ligature (which is wrong). In settings.json I added the line "editor.fontLigatures": true, to activate ligatures. Example (to test it, needs ligature font, like Fira Code): 
public class Ligature_Test
{
    //  Note: Unicode-Character U+200C (ZERO_WIDTH_NON_JOINER)
    //          prevents ligatures in comments.
    public static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        double a = 2.0, b = 3.0;

        if(a < b) { }   // <
        if(a > b) { }   // >
        if(a <= b) { }  // <=
        if(a >= b) { }  // >=
        if(a == b) { }  // == 
        if(a != b) { }  // !=

        // Lambda          =>
        Action action = () => Console.WriteLine("Hello World");

        // Additionals:
        // && instead of &&
        // || instead of ||
        // ?? instead of ??
        // ?. instead of ?.
        // // instead of //
        // /* and */ instead of /* and */
    }
}

Issue Type: Bug I previously opened this issue [here](https://github.com/microsoft/vscode-pull-request-github/issues/2281), however it was determined that because the extension is using a webview, the `when` clause isn't properly met, which is an issue that VScode would have to handle in order to make sure that it has consistent enforcement across any extension with webviews: > I have the following keybinding: > > ``` > { > "key": "space", > "command": "vspacecode.space", > "when": "!whichkeyActive && !inputFocus && !textInputFocus" > }, > ``` > > This works perfectly fine pretty much everywhere I've tried, except in the comment field in the sidebar when I go to approve/request changes on a PR. When I hit "Space", the above command gets invoked, even though I believe that technically that text field should have focus (and thus should be ignored based on the above `when` clause). > > Am I missing something? Is there a "proper" when clause so that I can leave "Space" mapped to that command? Otherwise I guess I'll still need to use the web interface (which is what I'm trying to void by using this extension in the first place ) > > Any pointers would be much appareciated. Thanks! > > > - Extension version: 0.21.0 > - VSCode Version: 1.51.0 > - OS: macOS 10.15.7 > > Steps to Reproduce: > > 1. Set up the above keybinding with [the VSpaceCode extension](https://github.com/VSpaceCode/VSpaceCode) installed > and properly configured. > 2. Try typing in a PR's comment field and hit "Space" > 3. VSpaceCode is invoked, despite the `when` clause seemingly not being true. IMO, if I'm in a text/input field (regardless of whether or not I'm in a web view or not - as a user I can't be expected to know what's a web view and what's native UI elements) the above `when` clause should work. Opening this as a bug to reflect that. Any pointers about how to make this work would be very much appreciated. Thanks! Hello. I am using vs code and ms-dotnettools.csharp extension to debug an external .exe process written in C# .NET 4.6 Framework. I am attaching to this process with below configuration

```
"configurations": [
     {
         "name": "Attach to ConsoleApp",
         "type":"clr",
         "request": "attach",
         "processName": "ConsoleApp",
     }]
```

This works pretty fine to the point when I close Visual Studio Code after a breakpoint is hit and make some debug steps. The application to which the process was attached crashes without any information, even the windows Event viewer is empty of any information. However, stopping the debugger, without closing the VSCode works very fine, this is why I assume this could be a vscode issue, not the C# extension itself. Although this crash is not happening each time, for example, I more often reproduce it on a slower VM than on a faster local system.

What happens when VSCode is closing? Will it stop the running extension gracefully?


<!-- Use Help > Report Issue to prefill these. -->
- VSCode Version: 1.51.1
- OS Version: Windows 10.0.18363
- ms-dotnettools.csharp Version: 1.23.6

Steps to Reproduce:

1. Build a .NET x64 exe application with DebugType portable
2. Run the exe.
3. Open VSCode with C# extension.
4. Run the debugger that will attach to the running exe.
5. Place a breakpoint.
6. Breakpoint is hit.
7. Make some debug steps.
8. Close Visual Studio Code.
9. The .exe to which the debugger was attached crashes without any information.

<!-- Launch with `code --disable-extensions` to check. -->
Does this issue occur when all extensions are disabled?: No. This issue requires the ms-dotnettools.csharp extension

I asked the same question/bug report on [StackOverflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/65143468/visual-studio-code-on-exit-kills-a-external-exe-process-to-which-a-c-sharp-debu)

Hello, I was using typescript, but the global typings apparently crashed after clicking on a quick vscode correction suggestion.
After clicking on ``Define ...``, VSCode is throwing ``Cannot find name error ...`` like ``Cannot find name 'Object'.`` in ``.ts`` files and  ``Cannot find global type 'Boolean'.`` in ``tsconfig.json`` files. 

I already knew that error can be fixed with ``compilerOptions.target`` option in tsconfig.json, but I clicked quick fix suggestion of vscode to fix faster than but there is a bug(i suppose it was bug).

All typings that I checked if had error ``Cannot find name error (or cannot find global type)`` are:
``Object``, ``Boolean``, ``Error (and the derivatives like TypeError)``, ``String``, ``Array``, ``Readonly``, ``Required``, ``parseInt``, ``encodeURI``, etc. 

Before that if it really is a bug and if I will receive updates to fix, there is some way to recover my typing file that it was before I clicked `` Define ... ''?

Steps to Reproduce:

1. Create a project with tsconfig.json above.
2. Type ``Object.values`` in index.ts and see quick fixes available.
3. Click on ``Define values ...`` (I don't remember what the correct alternative was, but it was the first option starting with ``Define values``)

I frequently run into issues with the TS server, e.g. stale errors when switching branches or [renames not working properly](https://github.com/microsoft/TypeScript/issues/40386#issuecomment-726054257). It's not always obvious whether these issues are just slowness or whether the TS server has crashed.

As I understand it, if the TS server crashes, the user will _not_ be informed, and VS Code will restart the TS server.

I would like to be notified when the TS server crashes, so I can investigate and file an issue with steps to reproduce.

I appreciate it doesn't make sense for this to be the default behaviour, but a setting would be very useful for users like me who do want to help investigate issues in TS server, or provide feedback when an issue occurs.

I understand this behaviour [already exists in insiders](https://twitter.com/OliverJAsh/status/1326869727164174337), however I do not want to use insidersI want to remain on the stable version.

Issue Type: Bug Extension webview does'nt ask for permission for user media , The vscode api for extensions provides us with methods to create webviews , but we can run scripts through this webview and get access to users media devices such as their camera and microphone. For my local environment no permissions were asked to access these resources. I've developed a basic extension to demonstrate this issue , you can find it here : - https://github.com/sastaachar/vscode-demo To reproduce , clone the repo , install node and npm , npm i -> to install all dependencies npm run watch -> to compile and watch for changes After this you can open the debug window to run the extension locally. Issue Type: Bug 1. Install 1.53 Insider (my tests have been in portable mode) 1. Install either kelvin.sshfs or liximomo.remotefs 1. Configure an SSH connection to a RHEL 6 host 1. Add connection as workspace folder (crash may occur before this step with liximomo) VS Code version: Code - Insiders 1.53.0-insider (c265dff48a27868c7f0f84fd25a169897dc43d73, 2021-01-14T06:31:42.082Z) OS version: Windows_NT x64 10.0.21292 Also reported SchoofsKelvin/vscode-sshfs#225 but at least at the time, he was unable to reproduce the crash, which I am guessing - since I only just discovered this was relevant - is because he was not trying to connect to a RHEL 6 host. As I mentioned in the other issue, I just discovered that the crash doesn't seem to happen when connecting to RHEL 7.3. Both extensions work fine with the same connection configurations on 1.52.0-insider (dbbf7079b20b3036b3ff5ac2e2106b84dd3c6d66, 2020-12-10T17:20:40.435Z). The crash _seems_ to happen - I think - during the check for various potential configuration files in the workspace folder (.vscode, .git, .devcontainer, etc.), but I don't know whether those are causing it or if the timing might be coincidental. I looked into using the official Remote SSH extension instead, but it doesn't seem to allow a remote workspace folder in the current session rather than the remote session taking over, and isn't compatible with the hosts I need to connect to anyhow.

Steps to Reproduce:

1. Create a new extension
2. Install `onnxruntime` package
3. Load any ONNX model
4. Create a correct input to the model and modify the data type of one of the inputs to force an error
5. Run the model with the input
6. Expected behavior: Model execution fail and throws a catchable exception
7. Actual behavior: Extension crashes without any error or exception

**Running the same code above in node produces a catchable exception.**

After debugging and looking through onnxruntime source code, it looks like the native code fails at [ORT_ENFORCE](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/afd7b8b3f751e7aedbea708282003c380084606a/include/onnxruntime/core/common/common.h#L180) which throws a C++ exception (which somehow does not get propagated back).

<!-- Launch with `code --disable-extensions` to check. -->

Clicking the "refresh" button at the top of the tree correctly expands the tree with the current file selected. It takes flicking back and forth between two files several times to reproduce, but it happens randomly during the course of normal usage. This happens with and without extensions enabled. Load VS Code on Raspberry PI. Open a menu. The main VSCode menus are affected in the same way as the bug reporter shown in the screen cap. Rendered contents of half of the menus are skewed 45 degrees (a stride issue somewhere in rendering). I have set my display depth to 32 bits. You may need to do this to repro. Raspberry PI devices use 16-bit display buffers by default. Add ``` framebuffer_depth=32 framebuffer_ignore_alpha=1 ``` to `/boot/config.txt` if necessary. ![sshot](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/11447564/107597271-29a20200-6be8-11eb-959b-28c481c0e760.png) VS Code version: Code 1.53.1 (5d424b828ada08e1eb9f95d6cb41120234ef57c7, 2021-02-08T23:25:09.298Z) OS version: Linux arm 5.10.11-v7l+

- VS Code Version: 1.53
- OS Version: Windows 10 version 20H2 build 19042.746

Steps to Reproduce:

1. Open VS Code
2. Open more VS Code windows or other programs (~3 more)
3. To start fresh again, restart the computer

Result: A some point VS Code starts up but stays in the dark gray startup screen. Already opened windows also freeze in their current state.

However all windows still work just fine, you can edit stuff in them, run commands or get hints when hovering the mouse over where the side bar is. So it seems to be a graphical error.

Downgrading to 1.52 seemed to help. Other fixes, like running --disable-gpu, deleting cache, reinstalling or using insiders has not helped.

Issue Type: Bug The crash occurs when the InterSystems Language Server extension is activated. The extension calls out from JavaScript to an InterSystems shared library (packaged with the extension) and then uses the following Node FFI modules to turn the returned result into JavaScript objects: - ffi-napi 4.0.3 - ref-array-napi 1.2.2 - ref-napi 3.0.2 - ref-struct-napi 1.1.1 Although we have been using older versions of these modules the crash also occurs with these latest versions of them. This works fine with VSCode Stable (and has done for months) but crashes on Insiders. It also works fine with stand-alone Node. The crash actually occurs when the JavaScript code either uses `toArray` or attempts to access a part of the returned object using subscripting (i.e. `[..]`). The last JS code executed before calling native code is in ref-napi: ref.js calls `_reinterpret` to "reinterpret" the buffer by - as I understand it - creating a larger buffer at the same address. I have attached a zip of the .dmp file created by VSCode Insiders. ER: The Language Server extension starts up and functions normally AR: The Language Server crashes on activation and (after a retry) disconnects from the client.
